HEADWORD: Selvedge
<hw>Sel"vedge</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Self</ets> + <ets>edge</ets>, i. e., its own
proper edge; cf. OD. <ets>selfegge</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
edge of cloth which is woven in such a manner as to prevent
raveling.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The edge plate of a lock, through which the bolt
passes.</def> <rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining.)</fld> <def>A layer of clay or decomposed
rock along the wall of a vein. See <er>Gouge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
4.</def> <rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Selvedged</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Selvaged</ent>⟦br⟧
